<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="487" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,433,998]" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,433,458]" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Head weakly to strongly produced. Pronotum with sublateral longitudinal carinae absent or if present, weakly developed and not extended entire length. Forewings with claval veins separate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="487" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,433,998]" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,505,530]" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">Remarks</emphasis>
. The genus can readily be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant" authorityName="Distant" box="[821,973,505,530]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Preta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[821,882,506,529]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">Preta</emphasis>
Distant
</taxonomicName>
, the only other Oriental genus by the lack of paired complete carinae on the pronotum (present in 
<taxonomicName box="[798,859,542,565]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Preta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[798,859,542,565]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">Preta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and separate claval veins on forewings (fused in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,212,578,601]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Preta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,212,578,601]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">Preta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,433,998]" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">
The aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[366,521,613,638]" captionStart="FIGURES 98 – 104" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1946,1969]" captionTargetBox="[180,1401,208,1907]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[165,1412,193,1920]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 98 – 104. Signoretia aureola Distant. 98. Male genital capsule except subgenital plates, lateral view; 99. Process of segment X; 100. Connective, dorsal view; 101. Style, dorsal view; 102. Aedeagus, lateral view; 103. Ventral process of aedeagus, posterior view; 104. Adeagus, posterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/167199/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">Figs 102, 104</figureCitation>
) in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[677,793,614,637]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Signoretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="487" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[677,793,614,637]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">Signoretia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite complex. Often the shaft and atrium are joined to a Y-shaped well sclerotized ventral process (“ventral paraphysis-like process” of 
<bibRefCitation author="Takiya" box="[1099,1315,649,674]" pageId="1" pageNumber="487" refString="Takiya, D. M., Dietrich, C. H. &amp; Viraktamath, C. A. (2013) The unusual Afrotropical and Oriental leafhopper subfamily Signoretiinae (Hemiptera, Cicadellidae): taxonomic notes, new distributional records, and description of two new Signoretia species. Zookeys, 319, 303 - 323." type="journal article" year="2013">
Takiya 
<emphasis box="[1186,1245,649,673]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">et al.</emphasis>
2013
</bibRefCitation>
) either by membranous or sclerotized structure or a distinct articulation. The latter in turn articulates with the connective anteriorly and the arms are variously directed. In some cases the arms cross over each other at the base and are covered either sparsely or densely with short setae on the dorsal surface (
<figureCitation box="[988,1148,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURES 133 – 139" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1821,1844]" captionTargetBox="[165,1419,206,1786]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[150,1436,193,1800]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 133 – 139. Signoretia mishmiensis sp. nov. 133. Male genital capsule, lateral view; 134. Subgenital plate, ventral view; 135. Style, dorsal view; 136. Aedeagus and ventral process, lateral view; 137. Aedeagus, dorsal view; 138. Connective, dorsal view; 139. Ventral process of aedeagus, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/167203/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">Figs 136, 139</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1161,1265,758,782]" captionStart="FIGURES 176 – 182" captionStartId="29.[151,264,1853,1876]" captionTargetBox="[166,1427,207,1817]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,193,1832]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURES 176 – 182. Signoretia sinuata sp. nov. 176. Male genital capsule, lateral view; 177. Subgenital plate, ventral view; 178. Style, lateral view; 179. Connective and ventral process of aedeagus, ventral view; 180. Aedeagus and ventral process, lateral view; 181. Aedeagus, anterodorsal view; 182. Female seventh sternite, ventral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/167209/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">179, 180</figureCitation>
). The aedeagal shaft is often membranous or partially or completely sclerotized, with a dorsal apodeme connected by a membranous or sclerotized structure with segment X; ventrally the shaft is preceded by what appears to be a gutterlike long (rarely short) atrium that is connected ventrally to the ventral process. The atrium also may possess one or two pairs of short finger-like processes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,433,998]" pageId="1" pageNumber="487">The genus now contains 16 Afrotropical and 20 Oriental species including the nine new species described below.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
